qas.question: Who has identified the island as an Important Antarctic Area?
There are 13 species of resident land birds on the islands and how many species of breeding seabirds?
There are 2 species of breeding seabirds on the island and how many species of resident land birds?
Where is the only known breeding site of the Tristan Petrel?

context: Tristan is primarily known for its <b4_0>wildlife<b4_0/>. The island has been identified as an Important Bird Area by <b0_0>BirdLife International<b0_0/> because there are <b2_0>13<b2_0/> known species of breeding seabirds on the island and <b1_0>two<b1_0/> species of resident land birds. The seabirds include northern rockhopper penguins, Atlantic yellow-nosed albatrosses, sooty albatrosses, Atlantic petrels, great-winged petrels, soft-plumaged petrels, broad-billed prions, grey petrels, great shearwaters, sooty shearwaters, Tristan skuas, Antarctic terns and brown noddies. <b3_0>Tristan and Gough Islands<b3_0/> are the only known breeding sites in the world for the Atlantic petrel (Pterodroma incerta; IUCN status EN). Inaccessible Island is also the only known breeding ground of the Spectacled Petrel (Procellaria conspicillata; IUCN Vulnerable). The Tristan albatross (IUCN status CR) is known to breed only on Gough and Inaccessible Islands: all nest on Gough except for one or two pairs who nest on Inaccessible Island.
